40
00:09:37.902 --> 00:09:39.528
<i>To the sky?</i>

41
00:09:44.575 --> 00:09:46.702
It was terrible.

42
00:09:57.713 --> 00:09:59.840
No one can describe it.

43
00:09:59.924 --> 00:10:02.260
No one can...

44
00:10:03.511 --> 00:10:07.640
recreate what happened here.

45
00:10:09.684 --> 00:10:12.436
Impossible!
And no one can understand it.


46
00:10:13.271 --> 00:10:15.982
Even I, here, now.

47
00:10:23.864 --> 00:10:26.284
<i>I can't believe I'm here.</i>

48
00:10:29.120 --> 00:10:31.914
<i>No, I just can't believe it.</i>

49
00:10:44.135 --> 00:10:46.929
<i>It was always this peaceful here.</i>

50
00:10:48.097 --> 00:10:54.103
<i>When they burned 2,000 people...
Jews... every day,</i>


51
00:10:54.353 --> 00:10:56.439
<i>it was just as peaceful.</i>

52
00:10:58.733 --> 00:11:02.528
<i>No one shouted.
Everyone went about his work.</i>


53
00:11:02.903 --> 00:11:05.031
<i>It was silent. Peaceful.</i>

54
00:11:05.781 --> 00:11:07.825
<i>Just as it is now.</i>

55
00:11:36.687 --> 00:11:40.399
<i>You, girl, don't you cry.</i>

56
00:11:40.483 --> 00:11:43.277
<i>Don't be so sad.</i>

57
00:11:43.611 --> 00:11:46.739
<i>For the dear summer is nearing...</i>

58
00:11:47.114 --> 00:11:49.033
<i>and I'll return with it.</i>

59
00:11:49.367 --> 00:11:52.620
<i>A mug of red
wine, a slice of roast,</i>

60
00:11:52.703 --> 00:11:55.956
<i>that's what the girls
give their soldiers.</i>


61
00:12:03.297 --> 00:12:06.384
<i>When the soldiers march along,</i>

62
00:12:06.717 --> 00:12:09.970
<i>the girls open their doors and windows.</i>

63
00:12:22.233 --> 00:12:26.320
<i>They thought the Germans
made him sing on the river.</i>


64
00:12:30.533 --> 00:12:32.993
<i>He was a toy to amuse them.</i>

65
00:12:34.495 --> 00:12:36.497
<i>He had to do it.</i>

66
00:12:36.831 --> 00:12:39.291
<i>He sang, but his heart wept.</i>

67
00:12:44.046 --> 00:12:47.425
<i>Do their hearts weep
thinking about that now?</i>


68
00:12:48.676 --> 00:12:50.219
<i>Certainly, very much so.</i>

69
00:12:57.184 --> 00:13:00.438
<i>They still talk about it
around the family table.</i>


70
00:13:03.399 --> 00:13:06.152
<i>It was public, so everyone knew of it.</i>

71
00:13:11.866 --> 00:13:15.202
<i>He said that was true German irony,</i>

72
00:13:18.080 --> 00:13:20.749
<i>people were being killed,
and he had to sing.</i>


73
00:13:22.418 --> 00:13:24.545
<i>That's what I thought.</i>

74
00:13:27.548 --> 00:13:30.301
What died in him in Chelmno?

75
00:13:39.643 --> 00:13:41.145
<i>Everything died.</i>

76
00:13:41.228 --> 00:13:44.231
<i>But he's only human,
and he wants to live.</i>


77
00:13:44.315 --> 00:13:46.650
<i>So he must forget.</i>

78
00:13:47.985 --> 00:13:51.697
__ The other survivor:
MICHAEL PODCHLEBNIK - ISRAEL


79
00:14:07.963 --> 00:14:12.510
<i>He thanks God for what remains
and that he can forget.</i>


80
00:14:12.593 --> 00:14:14.637
